	(25,1,'2016-06-09 00:33:10','2016-06-09 00:33:10','[:sr]<p style=\"text-align: right;\"></p><p style=\"text-align: right;\"><em><span style=\"font-size: 16px;\">One could fabulate, desperately, a sequence for crisis, but never without nostalgias subterfuge... suddenly you are draining the tanks of motorcycles for molotovs, as if the present in someones past was perceptibly arriving.</span></em></p><p style=\"text-align: right;\"><span style=\"font-size: 16px;\">- Jackqueline Frost, The Antidote</span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong><span style=\"font-size: 20px;\">0</span></strong></p><p><span style=\"font-size: 20px;\">Znate onaj osecaj kada se probudite ujutru sa utiskom da vam se u grudima stiska nekakvo nepoznato bice nametljivo nastojeci da se oslobodi; i vi pokuavate da diete sasvim lagano, kroz nos, kao da ste kakav budusticki monah koji se zagreva za prosvetljenje; i vae misli nisu ba u panici, ali znaju tacno kako panika izgleda? Eto, to je nepodnoljiva sadanjost, teka i neizbena kao gravitacija.</span></p><p><strong><span style=\"font-size: 20px;\">1</span></strong></p><p><span style=\"font-size: 20px;\">Kada je futurizam zavrteo svoj motor u Italiji i Rusiji, obe ove zemlje bile su relativno nerazvijene u ekonomskom smislu; ipak, vec su jasno mogle da naslute nadolazecu industrijalizovanu buducnost, upisanu u tlo susednih drava kao to su Nemacka</span><span style=\"font-size: 20px;\">i Ujedinjeno Kravljevstvo. Marineti (Marinetti) je napisao daje velicanstvenost sveta obogacena novom lepotom: lepotom brzine (The Manifesto of Futurism, 1909.). Njegova nameraje bila estetska  da pokae da je tutnjajuci automobil koji izgleda kao da je uzjahao mitraljez lepi nego skulptura Nike sa Samotrake  ali kao i slucaju mnogih drugih trkaca, njegovo odredite bilo je nejasno.</span></p><p><strong><span style=\"font-size: 20px;\">10</span></strong></p><p><span style=\"font-size: 20px;\">Futurizam je svoj volan upravio pravo u faizam, a Marinetijev auto protutnjao je kroz pokolj Drugog svetskog rata, guma lepljivih i skliskih od ljudskih ostataka totalnog rata. Ovde se krije i razlog zbog koga je sadanjost tako nepodnoljiva: mi sumnjamo da je gorivo za Marinetijev velicanstveni auto bila krv, i da je sav napredak koji smo napravili bio samo da bi se platilo za benzin. Ovo je praceno osecajem da se neka vrsta ponora nalazi tacno ispred nas, a da smo mi zarobljeni u vozilu koje ubrzava bez ikakve mogucnosti da iz njega izaemo. Moda ako bismo mogli da ostanemo u punom gasu i tako ubrzamo kroz horor istorije?</span></p><p><strong><span style=\"font-size: 20px;\">11</span></strong></p><p><span style=\"font-size: 20px;\">Filozof Nik Land (Nick Land) konkretizovao je uverenje da sama brzina kapitalizma moe proizvesti globalnu tranziciju ka do sada nevienoj tehnolokoj singularnosti (Manifesto for an Accelerationist Politics, 2013.), koja se, opte uzev, shvata kao tacka u kojoj mocna vetacka inteligencija moe da dizajnirajo inteligentnije maine bez ikakve ljudske intervencije. Akceleracionizam koji se u ovom smislu naslanja na Landa, ima nameru da ubrza isti proces tehnoloke evolucije kao i futuristi, ali za razliku od njih, njihov cilj nije tehno-utopijski. Dok se tehno-utopisti zalau za (tehnoloko prim.prev.) ubrzanje koje bi automatski prevazilo drutveni konflikt, kae Manifesto za akceleracionisticku politiku, naa pozicija je da tehnologija treba da bude ubrzana kako bi se u drutvenim sukobima pobeivalo.</span></p><p><strong><span style=\"font-size: 20px;\">100</span></strong></p><p><span style=\"font-size: 20px;\">Nik Land se namerno povukao iz sveta akademske filozofije[fusnota]Landovo povlacenje pretvorilo ga je u jednog od Velikih Starih savremene filozofije  svojevrsno natprirodno bice koje drema u skrivenim krajevima, koga sa icekivanjem gone poremeceni sledbenici. Veliki Stari originalno su izum pisca H.P. Lovkrafta (Lovecraft)  to je sasvim primereno obzirom da je i sam Land napisao dva lovkraftovska filozofska romana.[/fusnota], narocito nakon to je sa akceleracionizma preao na neoreakcionarnu poziciju, koju sam opisuje kao ubrzanje sa ispumpanom gumom (Re-Acceleration, 2013.). Marijentijev tutnjajuci auto konacno je zaustavljen. Neoreakcija takoe je poznata i kao mracno prosvetiteljstvo zato to njeni sledbenici odbacuju celokupan prosvetiteljski projekat demokratskog napretka (The Dark Enlightenment, year unknown). Umesto toga, koreni neoreakcije su u tehno-libertarijanskoj kulturi interneta koja se samoromantizuje kao razbojnicka iako je vie nego ikada u krevetu sa Volstritom, a koja pociva na fundamentalizmu slobodnog trita, razmejuci sebe kao kulturu neravnomernog individualizma uprkos cinjenici da se zasniva na masivnim iako mahom nevidljivim komunitarnim privatim i javnim mreama, povrh vladinih subvencija i regulacije (Borsook, 2001. Cyberselfish: Ravers, Guilders, Cyberpunks, And Other Silicon Valley Life Forms). Upravo ovo predstavlja orue kojim filozofi-kraljevi Silikonske doline misle da nam donesu buducnost; meutim, buducnost koji oni zamiljaju ne mora biti i buducnost koju mi za sebe elimo. Piter Til (Peter Thiel)  suosnivac Paypal-a i diplomac filozofije sa Stenforda  jednostavno je ovo saeo: Vie ne verujem da su sloboda i demokratija kompatibilne (The Education of a Libertarian, 2009.).</span></p><p><strong><span style=\"font-size: 20px;\">101</span></strong></p><p><span style=\"font-size: 20px;\">Meutim, neoreakcionarni pogled koji prosvetiteljstvo vidi kao mit progresa nije ogranicen samo na desnicu; mracna stranane bira ideologije. Kao i u slucaju akceleracionizma, osnivaci projekta mracne planine dolaze sa levice, iako u svojoj zelenoj pre nego crvenoj varijanti. Njihov poziv za od-civilizaciju je eksplicitno ekoloki  za njih je mit napretka ukorenjen u mitu prirode, a snovi futurista ne samo da nisu besplatni, vec je njihova cena zapravo toliko visoka da moe biti placena samo propacu civilizacije same. Daglas Hajn (Douglas Hine) i Pol Kingsnort (Paul Kingsnorth), autori Manifesta mracne planine ne veruju da ce sve biti u redu. Kako sami kau: Ukoliko poemo od postojecih definicija napretka i prosperiteta, mi cak nismo sigurni ni da elimo da sve bude u redu (Uncivilisation: The Dark Mountain Manifesto, 2009.).</span></p><p><strong><span style=\"font-size: 20px;\">110</span></strong></p><p><span style=\"font-size: 20px;\">Hajn ipak ne smatra da je manifesto apokaliptican, ukazujuci na njegov poslednji princip koji kae da kraj sveta kakvog poznajemo ne znaci i kraj sveta  tacka. Meutim, ovo nije narocito ubedljivo. Manifesto takoe govori o tome kako obrasci obicnog ivota, u kojem toliko toga ostaje isto iz dana u dan, maskiraju krhkost njegovog tkanja, tkanjakoje se moe rasplesti alarmantnom brzinom. Nepredvidive klimatske promene, u narativu manifesta, konacno na videlo iznose nau ultimativnu nemoc, ali zajednica okupljena oko projekta mracne planine ne pokuava tu moc da prigrabi nazad. Prepoznajuci umesto toga da je na svet i dalje oblikavan pricama, njihov predlog je da upravo pricama odgovore na neumitnu propast civilizacije; nastojeci da pomere na svetonazor kroz necivilizovano pisanje[fusnota]Manifesto definie necivilizovano pisanje kao pisanje koje pokuava da ostane izvan ljudskog mehura, u nameri da nas vidi onakvim kakvi zaista jesmo: visoko razvijeni majmuni sa mnotvom talenata i sposobnosti koje oslobaamo bez dovoljno razmiljanja, kontrole, saosecanja ili pameti.[/fusnota] , kako bismo ovaj slom prihvatili sa gracioznocu.</span></p><p><strong><span style=\"font-size: 20px;\">111</span></strong></p><p><span style=\"font-size: 20px;\">Ursula Le Gvin (Le Guin), proslavljena spisateljica naucne fantastike, napisala je da su postojala velika drutva koji nisu koristila tocak, ali da nije bilo niti jednog koje nije pricalo price (The Language of the Night: Essays on Fantasy and Science Fiction, 1980.) i ovo je jedan od nacina da se gleda na razliku izmeu coveka i ivotinje. Mi zamiljamo buducnost; tacnije, zamiljamo svoju smrt u toj buducnosti, i price koje pricamo nam slue kao odbrana. One nam omogucavaju da se iznad smrti izdignemo u formi kulture, i ovo skladite znanja  u usmenoj, pisanoj ili digitalnoj formi  je temelj na kome gradimo. Meutim, problem je u tome to, kao i sa zgradama, nai temelji odreuju kako ce naposletku izgledati citava struktura.</span></p><p><strong><span style=\"font-size: 20px;\">1000</span></strong></p><p><span style=\"font-size: 20px;\">Na primer, manifest akceleracionisticke politike Karla Marksa (Marx) naziva paradigmaticnim misliocem ubrazanja; ali Marksova vizija tehnoloke buducnosti svodiva je na isti mehanicki raj koji su prieljkivali futuristi<span>[fusnota]Ili moda ne: Fragmenti o mainama (u nezavrenim Marksovim spisima Grundrisse, prvi put objavljenim tek 1939. godine) sugeriu da je Marks vec mislio mnogo ispred svog vremena, naslucujuci vec tada razvoj ekonomije znanja.[/fusnota]</span>. Berardijev post- futurizam (The Post-Futurist Manifesto, 2009.) ovaj problem prevazilazi predlogom da brzina treba da bude premetena iz carstva eksternih maina u podrucje informacija (Futurism and the reversal of the future, 2013.). U politickom smislu, meutim, pitanje onoga ko zapoveda ovim domenom postalo je podrucjem borbe jo od 1996. godine, kada su najraniji stanovnici sajberprostora vladama industrijskog sveta poslali deklaraciju nezavisnosti, proglaavajuci nae virtuelno sopstvo imunim na vau suverenost, iako i dalje pristajemo na vau vladavinu nad naim telima (Barlow, 1996. A Declaration of Cyberspace Independence). Blockchain tehnologija tako je postala zamena za izbornu kutiju, a drutveni ugovor je zamenjen pametnim ugovorom<span>[fusnota]Blockchain tehnologija je tehnologija na osnovu koje funkcionie kriptovaluta bitcoin. Pametni ugovori su nova forma ugovornih sporazuma koji su bazirani na blockchain tehnologiji i cija je osnovna karakteristika da se automatski izvravaju.[/fusnota]</span>.</span></p><p><strong><span style=\"font-size: 20px;\">1001</span></strong></p><p><span style=\"font-size: 20px;\">Ovakva tehno-utopijska vizija buducnosti meutim, izbegava pitanje sopstvene ideoloke pozicioniranosti, odnosno izbora izmeu levice i desnice, predstavljajuci svojevrsnu hibridnu veru [koja] srecno odgovara na ovu zagonetku verujuci u obe vizije istovremeno  i ne kritikujuci ni jednu od njih (Barbrook &amp; Cameron, 2007. The Californian Ideology). Ipak, nakon Snoudena (Snowden), ispostavlja se da naa virtuelno ja takoe nije imuno na NSA pijune naih suverenih vladara  ali srecom, tehno-libertarijanska kalifornijska ideologija nije poslednja stanica na naem putu. Berardi nam ovde nudi jo jedan koristan putokaz, govoreci o komunizimu kao terapiji singularizacije, gde se singulanost odnosi na agenta koji ne sledi niti jedno pravilo usklaenosti i ponavljanja, i nije uokvireno nikakvom istorijskom nunocu (Communism is back but we should call it the therapy of singularisation, 2009.).</span></p><p><strong><span style=\"font-size: 20px;\">1010</span></strong></p><p><span style=\"font-size: 20px;\">Prema tome, nae poslednje odredie je ultimativni proces singularizacije  tzv. tehnoloka singularnost koja se po prvi put pojavljuje 1958. godine u citulji matematicaru Donu fon Nojmanu (John von Neumann), u kojoj se opisuje kako je sve bri tehnoloki napredak, i drutvene promene koje su sa njim povezane, opcrtao konture pribliavanja nekoj sutinskoj singularnosti u istoriji [ljudske] rase, nakon cega ljudski ivot, kako ga danas poznajemo, ne moe ostati isti (Ulam, 1958. John von Neumann 1903-1957). Ovaj raskid sa istorijom je najjednostavnije razumeti u religijskim okvirima; Berardi veruje da smo suvie dugo iveli u ustajalom vremenu religije i da nas je internet snabdeo sa dovoljno brzine da bismo ovoj ustajalosti konacno uspeli da pobegnemo i odvezemo se preko neistraenih dolina nepoznatog.</span></p><p><strong><span style=\"font-size: 20px;\">1011</span></strong></p><p><span style=\"font-size: 20px;\">Ipak, teko da Beradi moe da nasluti da nas jedan novi Bog, mainski Bog, ceka u tim dolinama. Tehnoloka singularnost upravo je deo konstrukcije ovog Boga: vetacka inteligencija inteligentnija on onih koji su je napravili (tj. nas), koja dovodi do eksplozije novih vetackih inteligencija. Sutinsko pitanje prema tome jeste: kako da budemo sigurni da ovaj novi Bog nece biti Ktulu[fusnota]Ktulu, jedan od Velikih Starih, na koje sam referisao na pocetku, predstavlja simbol Lovkraftove kosmicisticke filozofije: Boga zapravo nema i covecanstvo je samo jedna nebitna vrsta u sasvim ravnodunom univerzumu.[/fusnota]? Zagovornici singularizacije veruju da najveci izazov covecanstva danas predstavlja upravo napor da se osigura da ova potencijalna vetacka inteligencija radi u nau korist, jer ukoliko bude neprijateljski nastrojena ili makar ravnoduna, sa civilizacijom ce zasigurno biti gotovo istog trenutka. Mainski Bog jo uvek ne postoji, ali uprkos tome vec ima svoje jevaneliste, a oni ga se plae jednako koliko se plae i smrti.</span></p><p><strong><span style=\"font-size: 20px;\">1100</span></strong></p><p><span style=\"font-size: 20px;\">Ovaj ne-singularni strah od smrti tako cini podtekst mnogih miljenja o tehnolokoj singularnosti. Dva vodeca zagovornika prijateljske vetacke inteligencije, Rej Kurcvejl (Ray Kurzweil) i Elizer Judkovski (Eliezer Yudkowsky), javno su pisali o svom strahu o smrti. Judkovski radi u senci prerane smrti svog brata; Kurcvejl oplakuje ranu smrt svog oca usled bolesti srca i uzima 250 pilula dnevno i 6 intervenoznih terapija nedeljno kako bi produio svoj ivot. Ljudski strah od smrti  to jest strah od buducnosti  zastupnici singularizacije pretvorili su u krstaki pohod. Nik Bostrom (Nick Bostrom), jo jedan od zagovornika vetacke inteligencije, napisao je pricu koja smrt, odnosno buducnost, prikazuje kao zmaja-tiranina kojeg covecanstvno konacno treba da svrgne (The Fable of the Dragon-Tyrant, 2005.) Da bi ljudska rasa preivela, ona mora prestati da postoji; vecina singularijanaca je pretplacena na ideju transhumanistickog ideala u kojoj tehnoloka singularnost donosi besmrtnost kroz kimijsko vencanje coveka i maine[fusnota]<em>Kimijsko vencanje Kristijana Rosenkrojca</em> jedno je kljucnih tekstova alhemije, alegorija koja opisuje Sveti Brak, cilj Velikog Dela Alhemije.[/fusnota].</span></p><p><strong><span style=\"font-size: 20px;\">1101</span></strong></p><p><span style=\"font-size: 20px;\">Ova postavka najbolje ilustruje preklapanje izmeu miljenja o tehnolokoj singularnosti i onih o propasti civilizacije: Bostromov Institut za buducnost covecanstva prepun je veoma pametnih ljudi koji naporno rade i razmiljaju o tome kako da izbegnemo izumiranje od raznih vrsta egzistencijalnih pretnji. I svi se slau u jednom: ako planeta nestane, svi nestajemo sa njom, tako da bi najsigurnije bilo da je ipak napustimo pre ovakvog raspleta. Glas ove kosmicke filozofije mogao se cuti vec 1920. godine u samo-napisanom epitafu ruskog naucnika Konstantina Ciolkovskog (Tsiolkovsky), koji nam kae da covek nece zauvek ostati na Zemlji; potraga za svetlocu i prostranstvom ce ga naterati da probije granice atmosfere, ispocetka sasvim bojaljivo, da bi na kraju osvojio citav svemir[fusnota]Kosmicka filozofija Ciolkovskog predstavlja suprotnost Lovkraftovom kosmicizmu; ali takoe i kosmizmu Huga de Garisa, istraivaca vetacke inteligencije, koji predlae stvaranje bogu-slicnih maina, uprkos uverenju da ce njihovo upostavljanje da odvede u rat sa giga-smrtnocu izmeu starih i novih inteligencija.[/fusnota]. Ovo je bio prvi bod u kaputu veoma razlicitih boja (dok god svaka boja predstavlja mrkli mrak svemira), a ovaj kaput trenutno nosi Elon Mask (Musk), cija kompanija SpaceX predstavlja prvu fazu u njegovom planu da kolonizuje Mars.</span></p><p><strong><span style=\"font-size: 20px;\">1110</span></strong></p><p><span style=\"font-size: 20px;\">Marinetijev auto nastavlja da ubrzava, ali sada je to Maskov Tesla, elektricni automobil koji beumno promice. Ono to Masku nedostaje u smislu kosmicke svesti Ciolkovskog, on nadoknauje instinktom za preivljavanje, racunajuci da covecanstvo ima vece anse za opstanak ukoliko postane multiplanetarna infekcija, sa Marsom kao nultim pacijentom. Ako Maskovi planovi da kolonizuje Mars mnogima zvucekao naucna fantastika, to je delimicno zato to mu je, kao i svim preduzetnicima, stvaranje sopstvene mitologije jednako znacajno kao i stvaranje sopstvenog biznisa. A ta moe imati veci mitoloki naboj od osvajanja samog Boga Rata, planete cije crvenilo simbolie rubedo[fusnota]Rubedo (crvenilo na latinskom) je cetvrta, poslednja faza u Velikom Delu alhemije: stvaranje filozofskog kamena koji je sposoban da preobraava hemijske elemente.[/fusnota] alhemijskog kimijskog vencanja, tacku u kojoj otkrivamo svoju istinsku prirodu? Ipak, mogucnost kolonizovanja drugih delova solarnog sistema jeste realna, i ona samo zvuci kao naucna fantastika zato to je naucna fantastika o tome govorila mnogo pre Elona Maska.</span></p><p><strong><span style=\"font-size: 20px;\">1111</span></strong></p><p><span style=\"font-size: 20px;\">Nije slucajnost da se mnogi ovde pomenuti autori pojavljuju i kao pisci fikcije, ili da su njihova polazita ukorenjena u nekim ranijim pricama, narocito onima iz naucne fantastike i fikcije. Pisac Tomas Di (Thomas Disch) istakao je da su metafore naucne fantastike jo odavno inficirale nau svakodnevicu (The Dreams Our Stuff Is Made Of: How Science Fiction Conquered the World, 1998.) te da je naa postojeca tehnologija direktno inspirisana naucnom fantastikom  na primer, pronalazac mobilnog telefona Martin Kuper (Cooper) je bio pod uticajem zglobnog radija koji koristi Dik Trejsi (Dick Tracy), kao i ureaja za komunikaciju iz serijala Star Trek. Vilijam Gibson (William Gibson) iskusio je ovo vie od vecine, isticuci da je buducnost njegovih romana pocela da se stropotava u sadanjost do te mere da je na svoj rad poceo da referie kao na spekulativne romane veoma skore prolosti pre nego na spekulativne romane buducnosti[fusnota]Iz intervjua koji je dao <em>Wired</em> magazinu 2012. godine. Vie na: http://www.wired. com/2012/09/interview- with-william-gibson/[/fusnota].</span></p><p><strong><span style=\"font-size: 20px;\">10000</span></strong></p><p><span style=\"font-size: 20px;\">Kao i Gibson, svi ovde opisani pokreti odgovaraju na brzinu kojom putujemo kroz nepodnoljvu sadanjost. Njihove politike su veoma razlicite ali na slicnost prica koje pricaju ne moemo a da ne gledamo sa podozrenjem. Zapadne kulture su od hricanstva nasledile dva bukvalna metoda noenja sa nepodnoljivocu sadanjosti: Uznesenje i Apokalipsu. Apokalipsa govori o kraju svega, cesto da bi se moglo poceti iznova; dok nas Uznesenje die visoko iznad ruevina takoda moemo da gledamo dole dok se penjemo ka gore. Svaki od ovih pokreta ima svoju sopstvenu viziju apokalipse, a ta vizija odreuje kako da se ponaamo sada, kako da osmislimo neku vrstu uznesenja da bismo se suocili sa nepodnoljivom sadanjocu.</span></p><p><strong><span style=\"font-size: 20px;\">10001</span></strong></p><p><span style=\"font-size: 20px;\">Problem sa scenarijom apokalipse je to je prema skoro svakom metrickom pokazatelju razvojne ekonomije  stepen pismenosti odraslih, smrtnosti odojcadi, smrtnosti u konfiktima  bolje iveti danas nego u bilo kom drugom periodu istorije[fusnota]Ovaj podatak izneo je Carls Keni (Charles Kenny) iz Centra za globalni razvoj u svom clanku <em>The Best Year in History for the Average Human Being</em> iz 2015. godine. Meutim, na njegovu alost i dalje ne postoji neto takvo kao to je prosecno ljudsko bice. Clanak dostupan na: www.theatlantic. com/international/ archive/2015/12/good- news-in-2015/421200/[/fusnota]. Statisticar Hans Rosling (Dont Panic  How to End Poverty in 15 years, 2015.) i ekonomista Maks Rozer (Max Roser, ongoing, Our World in Data) posvetili su svoje karijere pomeranju narativa sa medijskog fokusa na katastrofama ka realnosti koja govori da ivimo u vreme prosperiteta bez presedana; Stiven Pinker (Stephen Pinker) je ubeen da nasilje u ljudskoj civilizaciji neprestano opada, i da je vreme u kome ivimo vreme do sada nevienog mira (The Better Angels of our Nature, 2011.). Ovo je gorka pilula za progutati, narocito za neke od nas koji naslucujemo apokalipsu; ali dobra vest je da ova vrsta optimizma ipak ne znaci da klimatske promene nisu stvarne, da tehnoloka singulanost ne stie, niti da ne ubrzavamo u pravcu politicke propasti.</span></p><p><strong><span style=\"font-size: 20px;\">10010</span></strong></p><p><span style=\"font-size: 20px;\">Ono to ovakva vienja zaista znace je da su drutvene, ekonomske i tehnoloke promene koje se deavaju svuda oko nas postale bre da nae sposobnosti da ih razumemo, ostavljajuci nas zaglavljene u slici sadanjosti koja stvarnost ne reflektuje ispravno. Na primer: nakon dekolonijalizacije, Zapad je razvio neuzdrmano uverenje da je africka ekonomija narativ neprestanog i neumitnog neuspeha, ali skoranja istraivanja sugeriu da ovaj neuspeh predstavlja statisticki artefakt koji vai samo ako ignoriemo 50-te, 60-te, 70-te, sve do 90-tih i 2000-tih (Morten, 2015. Africa: Why Economists Get It Wrong). Statistika je uvek podlona sumnji, i merenje je forma magije, ali ipak africke zemlje i dalje tancuju obrazovane mlade ljude u ekonomije u kojima za njih nema posla, to je naravno slucaj i sa Evropom, i njihov ekonomski napredak vezan je prevashodno za mree meunarodne trgovine koje izvoze robu  ili ljude. Migranti pristiu na evropske plae noseci mobilne telefone, i mi smo iznenaeni kada cujemo nau demografsku i tehnoloku buducnost kako nam trai ifru za wi-fi.</span></p><p><strong><span style=\"font-size: 20px;\">10100</span></strong></p><p><span style=\"font-size: 20px;\">Ovde opisani pokreti i pristupi su relativno mali u smislu brojnosti, ali nam ipak obezbeuju uvid, vrstu instrukcije. Oni su predstavljeni kao iskustvo preobracanja, oni predviaju Apokalipsu, i pozivaju svoje zagovornike da povedu civilizaciju prema Uznesenju. Zadatak prosvecenih je da brinu o nama ostalima na tom putovanju; Berardijevim recima, oni imaju ulogu da izau u susret onim [beznadenim, depresivnim i panikom obuzetim] ljudima, brinuci o njihovom ludilu, pokazujuci im da put ka srecnom prilagoavanju jeste priruci. Moda je Marineti bio u pravu kada je svoj automobil usmerio ka estetskim radije nego ka politickim ciljevima, iako je politika, naravno, uvek ugraena u estetiku. Nema nacina da se pobegne nepodnoljivoj sadanjosti, zato to se ona vec strovalila u buducnost, ali ako nita drugo, ove price nam mogu odvratiti panju od pejzaa koji sve bre promice sa druge strane prozora.</span></p><p><strong><span style=\"font-size: 20px;\">10101</span></strong></p><p><span style=\"font-size: 20px;\">U svojoj poslednjoj knjizi pre rane smrti, polticki naucnik Piter Mer (Peter Mair) napisao je da je postojeci model demokratske politike postao ispranjen kako su masovne politicke partije pocele da odumiru (Ruling the Void: the Hollowing of Western Democracy, 2014.). Ove partije su bile vozila naih prica, govoreci nam da su stvari nekada bile bolje nego to su sada i/ili da ce biti bolje u buducnosti. Kada Srnik i Vilijams (Srnicek &amp; Williams) kau da levica ne moe niti da ostane u sadanjosti niti da se vrati u prolost (Inventing the Future, 2015.), oni su samo delimicno u pravu, zato to ovde pomenuti pokreti sugeriu da cak ni u buducnost vie ne moemo da se vratimo. Kako su se prolost i buducnost stropotale u sadanjost, i levica i desnica potcinile su se politici sadanjosti; a oblik ove nove politike je nejasan, estoko osporavan i u permanentoj beta verziji. Marinetijev tutnjajuci automobil sada su samo-vozeca kola, koja cekaju na nekoga  bilo koga  da prezume volan.</span></p><p><strong><span style=\"font-size: 20px;\">GOTO 0</span></strong></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong><span style=\"font-size: 16px;\">Literatura</span></strong></p><ol><li><span style=\"font-size: 16px;\">Barbrook, Richard and Cameron, Andy (2007) <em>The Californian Ideology</em>. Dostupno na: <a href=\"http://www.comune.torino.it/gioart/big/bigguest/riflessioni/%20californian_engl.pdf\">http://www.comune.torino.it/gioart/big/bigguest/riflessioni/ californian_engl.pdf</a></span></li><li><span style=\"font-size: 16px;\">Barlow, John Perry (1996) <em>A Declaration of Cyberspace Independence</em>. Dostupno na: <a href=\"https://www.eff.org/cyberspace-independence\">https://projects.eff.org/~barlow/Declaration-Final.html</a></span></li><li><span style=\"font-size: 16px;\">Berardi, Franco (2009) <em>The Post-Futurist Manifesto</em>. Dostupno na: <a href=\"http://www.generation-online.org/p/fp_bifo5.htm\">http://www.generation-online.org/p/fp_bifo5.htm</a></span></li><li><span style=\"font-size: 16px;\">Berardi, Franco (2009) <em>Futurism and the reversal of the future</em>. Dostupno na: <a href=\"http://www.generation-online.org/p/fp_bifo8.htm\">http://www.generation-online.org/p/fp_bifo8.htm</a></span></li><li><span style=\"font-size: 16px;\">Berardi, Franco (2009) <em>Communism is back but we should call it the therapy of singularisation</em>. Dostupno na: <a href=\"http://www.generation-online.org/p/fp_bifo6.htm\">http://www.generation-online.org/p/fp_bifo6.htm</a></span></li><li><span style=\"font-size: 16px;\">Borsook, Paulina (2001) <em>Cyberselfish: Ravers, Guilders, Cyberpunks, And Other Silicon Valley Life Forms</em>. Dostupno na: <a href=\"http://digitalcommons.law.yale.edu/yjolt/%20vol3/iss1/1/\">http://digitalcommons.law.yale.edu/yjolt/ vol3/iss1/1/</a></span></li><li><span style=\"font-size: 16px;\">Bostrom, Nick (2005) <em>The Fable of the Dragon-Tyrant</em>. Dostupno na: <a href=\"http://www.nickbostrom.com/fable/dragon.html\">http://www.nickbostrom.com/fable/dragon.html</a></span></li><li><span style=\"font-size: 16px;\">Disch, T. (1998) <em>The Dreams Our Stuff Is Made Of: How Science Fiction Conquered the World</em>. Simon &amp; Schuster: New York.</span></li><li><span style=\"font-size: 16px;\">Hine, Dougals and Kingsnorth, Paul (2009) <em>Uncivilisation: The Dark Mountain Manifesto</em>. Dostupno na: <a href=\"http://dark-mountain.net/about/manifesto/\">http://dark-mountain.net/about/manifesto/</a></span></li><li><span style=\"font-size: 16px;\">Jerven, Morten (2015) Africa: Why Economists Get It Wrong. London: Zed Books.</span></li><li><span style=\"font-size: 16px;\">Land, Nick (2013) Re-Acceleration. Dostupno na: <a href=\"http://www.xenosystems.net/%20re-accelerationism/\">http://www.xenosystems.net/ re-accelerationism/</a></span></li><li><span style=\"font-size: 16px;\">Land, Nick (year unknown) <em>The Dark Enlightenment</em>. Dostupno na: <a href=\"http://www.thedarkenlightenment.com/the-dark-enlightenment-by-nick-land/\">http://www.thedarkenlightenment.com/the-dark-enlightenment-by-nick-land/</a></span></li><li><span style=\"font-size: 16px;\">Le Guin, Ursula (1980) The Language of the Night: Essays on Fantasy and Science Fiction. Ultramarine Publishing: New York.</span></li><li><span style=\"font-size: 16px;\">Mair, P. (2014), <em>Ruling the Void: the Hollowing of Western Democracy</em>. London: Verso Books.</span></li><li><span style=\"font-size: 16px;\">Marinetti, Filippo Tommaso (1909) <em>The Manifesto of Futurism</em>. Dostupno na: <a href=\"http://www.italianfuturism.org/manifestos/foundingmanifesto/\">http://www.italianfuturism.org/manifestos/foundingmanifesto/</a></span></li><li><span style=\"font-size: 16px;\">Pinker, S. (2011) <em>The Better Angels of our Nature</em>. New York, NY: Viking.</span></li><li><span style=\"font-size: 16px;\">Rosling, H. (2015) <em>Dont Panic  How to End Poverty in 15 years</em>. Dostupno na: <a href=\"https://www.gapminder.org/videos/dont-panic-end-poverty/\">http://www.gapminder.org/videos/dont-panic-end-poverty/</a></span></li><li><span style=\"font-size: 16px;\">Roser, M. (ongoing) <em>Our World in Data</em>. Dostupno na:<a href=\"http://ourworldindata.org\"> http://ourworldindata.org</a></span></li><li><span style=\"font-size: 16px;\">Srnicek, N. and Williams, A. (2015) <em>Inventing the Future</em>. London: Verso Books.</span></li><li><span style=\"font-size: 16px;\">Thiel, Peter (2009) <em>The Education of a Libertarian</em>. Dostupno na: <a href=\"http://www.cato-unbound.org/2009/04/13/peter-thiel/education-libertarian\">http://www.cato-unbound.org/2009/04/13/peter-thiel/education-libertarian</a></span></li><li><span style=\"font-size: 16px;\">Ulam, Stanislav (1958) <em>John von Neumann 1903-1957</em>, American Mathematical Society</span></li></ol>[:en]<p style=\"text-align: right;\"><span style=\"font-size: 16px;\"><i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">One could fabulate, desperately, a sequence for crisis, but never without nostalgias subterfuge... suddenly you are draining the tanks of motorcycles for molotovs, as if the present in someones past was perceptibly arriving.</span></i></span></p><p style=\"text-align: right;\"><span style=\"font-size: 16px;\"><i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">                                              -</span></i></span><span style=\"font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;\">Jackqueline Frost, The Antidote</span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"font-size: 20px;\"><b>0</b></span></p><p><span style=\"font-weight: 400; font-size: 20px;\">You know that feeling when you wake up in the morning, as if there was an alien in your chest cavity, waiting to break out; and you try to breathe calmly through your nose, as if you were a Buddhist monk warming up for enlightenment; and your thoughts aren\'t exactly in panic, but they know exactly what panic feels like? That\'s the unbearable present, weighing on you like gravity.</span></p><p><span style=\"font-size: 20px;\"><b>1</b></span></p><p><span style=\"font-size: 20px;\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">When Futurism started its engine in Italy and Russia, both countries were relatively backward in economic terms; but they could already see the industrialized future, written in the soil of neighbours such as Germany and the United Kingdom. Marinetti wrote that the worlds magnificence has been enriched by a new beauty: the beauty of speed (</span><i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">The Manifesto of Futurism</span></i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">, 1909.). His intent was aesthetic  to show that a roaring car that seems to ride on grapeshot is more beautiful than the Victory of Samothrace  but like so many boy racers, his destination was unclear.</span></span></p><p><span style=\"font-size: 20px;\"><b>10</b></span></p><p><span style=\"font-weight: 400; font-size: 20px;\">Futurism steered right into fascism, and Marinetti\'s roaring car sped through the carnage of the second world war, its tyres slick with the human remains of total war. Here is the reason why the present is unbearable: we suspect that the fuel for Marinetti\'s roaring car was blood, and that all the progress that we\'ve made was to pay for the gas. This is matched by a feeling that some kind of precipice is just ahead of us, and that we\'re trapped in a speeding vehicle with no way to get out. Perhaps if we keep our foot on the accelerator we can accelerate through this horror of history?</span></p><p><span style=\"font-size: 20px;\"><b>11</b></span></p><p><span style=\"font-size: 20px;\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">The philosopher Nick Land crystallised a belief that capitalist speed alone could generate a global transition towards unparalleled technological singularity (</span><i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Manifesto for an Accelerationist Politics</span></i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">, 2013.) generally understood to be the point at which strong artificial intelligence could design even more intelligent machines without human intervention. The </span><b>Accelerationism</b><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> that followed after Land wants to accelerate the same process of technological evolution as the Futurists but, unlike the Futurists, their goal is not techno-utopian. Whereas the techno-utopians argue for acceleration on the basis that it will automatically overcome social conflict, states the Manifesto for Accelerationist Politics, our position is that technology should be accelerated precisely because it is needed in order to win social conflicts.</span></span></p><p><span style=\"font-size: 20px;\"><b>100</b></span></p><p><span style=\"font-size: 20px;\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Nick Land deliberately withdrew from the world of academic philosophy[fusnota]Land\'s withdrawal turned him into the Great Old One of contemporary philosophy  a supernatural entity slumbering in hidden space, eagerly pursued by deranged acolytes, originally conceived by the writer H.P. Lovecraft  which is appropriate given Land has himself written two Lovecraftian philosophical novels.[/fusnota] as he graduated from accelerationism to </span><b>Neoreaction</b><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">, which he describes as accelerationism with a flat tire, (</span><i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Re-Acceleration</span></i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">, 2013.) bringing the roaring car to a halt. Neoreaction is also known as the Dark Enlightenment because its adherents reject the entire Enlightenment project of democratic progress (</span><i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">The Dark Enlightenment</span></i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">, year unknown). Their roots are instead in the techno-libertarian culture of the internet that romanticizes itself as outlaw when more than ever it\'s in bed with Wall Street based on free-market fundamentalism, self-concepts of rugged individualism in spite of massive but mostly invisible communitarian meshes of private and public networks on top of government subsidy and regulation (Borsook, 2001. </span><i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Cyberselfish: Ravers, Guilders, Cyberpunks, And Other Silicon Valley Life Forms</span></i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">). This is the means through which the philosopher-kings of Silicon Valley are poised to bring the future to us; yet the future they envisage might not be the future we see for ourselves. Peter Thiel  co-founder of PayPal and a Stanford philosophy graduate  summarized it simply: I no longer believe that freedom and democracy are compatible. (</span><i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">The Education of a Libertarian</span></i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">, 2009.).</span></span></p><p><span style=\"font-size: 20px;\"><b>101</b></span></p><p><span style=\"font-size: 20px;\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">However, the Neoreactionary view of the Enlightenment as a myth of progress is not restricted to the right wing; the dark has an appeal that cuts across party lines. As with accelerationism, the founders of the </span><b>Dark Mountain project</b><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> emerged from the left, albeit the green rather than the red variety. Their call for uncivilisation is explicitly ecological  that the myth of progress is founded on the myth of nature, that the dreams of the futurists are not cost-free, and that the cost is so high that it can only be paid in the coin of civilisation itself. Dougald Hine and Paul Kingsnorth, the authors of the Dark Mountain manifesto do not believe that everything will be fine. We are not even sure, based on current definitions of progress and improvement, that we want it to be (</span><i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Uncivilisation: The Dark Mountain Manifesto</span></i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">, 2009.).</span></span></p><p><span style=\"font-size: 20px;\"><b>110</b></span></p><p><span style=\"font-weight: 400; font-size: 20px;\">Hine has said that the Manifesto is not apocalyptic, pointing out that its last principle is that The end of the world as we know it is not the end of the world full stop, but this is unconvincing. The manifesto also talks about how the pattern of ordinary life, in which so much stays the same from one day to the next, disguises the fragility of its fabric, a fabric that can unravel at an alarming speed. Runaway climate change, in this narrative, brings home at last our ultimate powerlessness, and the Dark Mountain community does not attempt to claw back that power. Recognising instead that our world is still shaped by stories, it is with stories that they propose to respond to the collapse of civilisation; they seek to shift our worldview through uncivilised writing [fusnota]Uncivilised writing is defined in their manifesto as writing which attempts to stand outside the human bubble and see us as we are: highly evolved apes with an array of talents and abilities which we are unleashing without sufficient thought, control, compassion or intelligence.[/fusnota] to accept this collapse with grace.</span></p><p><span style=\"font-size: 20px;\"><b>111</b></span></p><p><span style=\"font-size: 20px;\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">The science fiction writer Ursula Le Guin wrote there have been great societies that did not use the wheel, but there have been no societies that did not tell </span><i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">stories, </span></i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">(</span><i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">The Language of the Night: Essays on Fantasy and Science Fiction</span></i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">, 1980.) and this is one way to</span> <span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">separate the human from the other animals. We visualise the future; more specifically, we visualise our own death in that future, and stories are our defense against death. They enable us to transcend death in the form of culture, and this store of knowledge  in oral, written or digital forms  is the foundation on which we build. The problem is that, like a building, our foundations determine what the structure will eventually look like.</span></span></p><p><span style=\"font-size: 20px;\"><b>1000</b></span></p><p><span style=\"font-size: 20px;\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">For example, the Accelerationist Manifesto calls Karl Marx the paradigmatic accelerationist thinker; but Marx\'s vision of the technological future would have been limited to the same mechanical paradise as the Futurists[fusnota]Or possibly not: the <em>Fragment on Machines</em> (pp. 690-712 of the unpublished <em>Grundrisse</em>) suggest that Marx was already thinking far ahead of his technological time, anticipating the knowledge economy.[/fusnota]. Berardi\'s Post-Futurism (</span><i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">The Post-Futurist Manifesto</span></i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">, 2009.) overcomes this by proposing that speed too has been transferred from the realm of external machines to the information domain. (</span><i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Futurism and the reversal of the future</span></i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">, 2013.). In political terms, however, the question of who commands this domain has been fought over ever since 1996, when the Governments of the Industrial World received a declaration of independence from the earliest citizens of cyberspace, describing our virtual selves immune to your sovereignty, even as we continue to consent to your rule over our bodies (Barlow, 1996. </span><i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">A Declaration of Cyberspace Independence</span></i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">). The blockchain replaces the ballot box, and the social contract becomes a Smart Contract[fusnota]The blockchain is the technology that the Bitcoin cryptocurrency runs on, while smart contracts are a new form of contractual agreement that are also based on blockchain technology.[/fusnota].</span></span></p><p><span style=\"font-size: 20px;\"><b>1001</b></span></p><p><span style=\"font-size: 20px;\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">This techno-utopian vision of cyberspace avoids the question of whether it is left-wing or right-wing, a hybrid faith [that] happily answers this conundrum by believing in both visions at the same time  and by not criticising either of them. (Barbrook &amp; Cameron, 2007. </span><i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">The Californian Ideology</span></i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">). Post-Snowden, it also turns out that our virtual selves are not immune to the NSA spymasters of our sovereign rulers  but luckily the techno-libertarian Californian Ideology is not the final stop in the journey. Berardi signposts it for us, talking of communism as the therapy of singularisation, where singularity refers to an agency that does not follow any rule of conformity and repetition, and is not framed in any historical necessity (</span><i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Communism is back but we should call it the therapy of singularisation</span></i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">, 2009.).</span></span></p><p><span style=\"font-size: 20px;\"><b>1010</b></span></p><p><span style=\"font-size: 20px;\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">So our final destination is the ultimate singularisation process  the Technological Singularity, first appearing in a 1958 obituary for the mathematician John von Neumann, which described how accelerating technological progress, and the associated social changes, gave the appearance of approaching some essential singularity in the history of the race beyond which human affairs, as we know them, could not continue (Ulam, 1958. </span><i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">John von Neumann 1903-1957</span></i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">). This break from history is best understood in religious terms; Berardi believes that we have lived in the stagnant time of religion for too long and that the Internet provides us with enough speed to achieve escape velocity, and to drive out across the empty plains of the unknown.</span></span></p><p><span style=\"font-size: 20px;\"><b>1011</b></span></p><p><span style=\"font-size: 20px;\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Little does Berardi know that a new God, a machine God, is waiting on those plains. The Technological Singularity consists of the construction of this God: an Artificial Intelligence (AI) more intelligent than those that artificed it (i.e. us), leading to an explosion of artificial intelligence. The essential question is: how do we ensure that our new God is not Cthulhu?[fusnota]Cthulhu, one of the Great Old Ones referred to in Footnote 3, symbolised H.P. Lovecraft\'s philosophy of cosmicism: that there is no God and that humanity is an insignificant species in an indifferent universe.[/fusnota] </span><b>Singularitarians</b><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> believe that humanity\'s greatest challenge is to ensure that this potential AI works to our benefit, since if it is hostile or merely indifferent to us, then civilization will come to an end almost immediately. This God does not yet exist, yet it already has its evangelists, and those evangelists are as afraid of it as they are of death.</span></span></p><p><span style=\"font-size: 20px;\"><b>1100</b></span></p><p><span style=\"font-size: 20px;\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">This non-singular fear of death seems to underpin much of Singularity thinking. Two leading advocates of \'Friendly AI\', Ray Kurzweil and Eliezer Yudkowsky, have written publicly of their fear of death. Yudkowsky works in the shadow of the early death of his brother; Kurzweil mourns the early death of his father from heart disease, and takes 250 pills per a day and six intravenous therapies per week to extend his own life. The human fear of death  that is, the fear of the future  is recast by Singularitarians as a crusade. Nick Bostrom, another AI advocate, wrote a fable that casts death  that is, the future  as a dragon-tyrant to be thrown off by humanity (</span><i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">The Fable of the Dragon-Tyrant, 2005.).</span></i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> In order for the human race to survive, however, it must cease to exist; most Singularitarians subscribe to the transhumanist ideal that the Singularity will deliver immortality through the chymical wedding of human and machine.[fusnota]The Chymical Wedding of Christian Rosenkreutz is one of the key texts of alchemy, an allegory describing the Sacred Marriage, the goal of the Great Work of Alchemy.[/fusnota]</span></span></p><p><span style=\"font-size: 20px;\"><b>1101</b></span></p><p><span style=\"font-weight: 400; font-size: 20px;\">This illustrates the large overlap between singularity thinking and civilisational collapse: Nick Bostrom\'s Future of Humanity Institute is filled with very smart people thinking very hard about how to avoid extinction from a range of existential threats. Everybody agrees on one thing: if the planet goes, we all go, and so the safest bet is to leave the planet ahead of that schedule. The voice of this cosmic philosophy can be heard in the self-written 1920 epitaph by the Russian scientist Konstantin Tsiolkovsky, telling us that Man will not always stay on Earth; the pursuit of light and space will lead him to penetrate the bounds of the atmosphere, timidly at first, but in the end to conquer the whole of solar space[fusnota]Tsiolkovsky\'s \'cosmic philosophy\' contrasts with Lovecraft\'s cosmicism; but also with the cosmism of AI researcher Hugo de Garis, who proposes the creation of godlike machines despite the belief that their creation will lead to a \'gigadeath war\' between the old and new intelligences.[/fusnota]. This was the first stitch in a coat of many colours (as long as every colour is the pitch black of space), and that coat is currently worn by the entrepreneur Elon Musk, whose company SpaceX represents the first stage in his plan to colonise Mars.</span></p><p><span style=\"font-size: 20px;\"><b>1110</b></span></p><p><span style=\"font-weight: 400; font-size: 20px;\">Marinetti\'s automobile races on, but now it is Musk\'s Tesla, an electric car that runs silently. What Musk lacks in Tsiolkovsky\'s cosmic awareness, he makes up for in survival instinct, calculating that humanity has more chance of surviving if it becomes a multiplanetary infection, with Mars as Patient Zero. If Musk\'s plans to colonise the red planet sound like science fiction to many people, this is partly because, like all entrepreneurs, creating his own mythology is almost as important as creating his own business. What could be more mythological than conquering the God of War himself, on a planet whose redness signifies the rubedo<span>[fusnota]Rubedo (redness in Latin) is the fourth, final stage in the Great Work of alchemy: the creation of the philosopher\'s stone capable of transmuting the elements.[/fusnota]</span> of the alchemists\' Chymical Wedding, the point at which we discover our true nature? Yet the possibility of colonising other parts of the solar system is real, and they only sound like science fiction because science fiction was talking about it long before Elon Musk.</span></p><p><span style=\"font-size: 20px;\"><b>1111</b></span></p><p><span style=\"font-size: 20px;\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">It\'s no coincidence that many of the writers associated with the positions described in this article double up as fiction writers, or that these positions are rooted in earlier stories, particularly from science fiction and fantasy. The writer Thomas Disch pointed out that the tropes of science fiction infested our ordinary lives long ago (</span><i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">The Dreams Our Stuff Is Made Of: How Science Fiction Conquered the World</span></i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">, 1998.) and many of our existing technologies were directly inspired by science fiction  Martin Cooper, the inventor of the mobile phone, for example, was influenced by the wrist radio used by Dick Tracy and the Communicator devices of Star Trek. William Gibson experienced this more than most, finding that the future timeline for his science fiction books was collapsing towards the present, to the extent that he began referring to his work as speculative novels, of the very recent past, rather than speculative novels of the future.[fusnota]From a 2012 interview with Wired magazine http://www.wired.com/2012/09/interview-with-william-gibson/[/fusnota]</span></span></p><p><span style=\"font-size: 20px;\"><b>10000</b></span></p><p><span style=\"font-weight: 400; font-size: 20px;\">Like Gibson, all of these movements are responding to the speed at which we\'re travelling through the unbearable present. Their politics are very different but the stories they tell are suspiciously similar. Western culture inherited from Christianity two literary methods to face the unbearable present: the Rapture and the Apocalypse. The Apocalypse calls everything to an end, often so that we can start again; the Rapture takes us high above the carnage so that we can look down as we move up. Each of the movements described here has its own vision of the Apocalypse, and that vision determines how they act now, to carve out some kind of Rapture for them to occupy in the unbearable present.</span></p><p><span style=\"font-size: 20px;\"><b>10001</b></span></p><p><span style=\"font-size: 20px;\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">The problem with the Apocalypse is that by nearly every development metric  adult literacy, infant mortality, conflict deaths  it is better to be alive today than at any time in history[fusnota]This case is laid out by Charles Kenny of the Centre for Global Development in his 2015 article, <em>The Best Year in History for the Average Human Being</em> (www.theatlantic.com/international/archive/2015/12/good-news-in-2015/421200/), although sadly there is no such thing as the average human being.[/fusnota]. The statistician Hans Rosling (</span><i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Dont Panic  How to End Poverty in 15 years</span></i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">, 2015.) and the economist Max Roser (Max Roser, ongoing, </span><i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Our World in Data</span></i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">) have both dedicated careers to shifting the narrative away from the media focus on catastrophe toward the reality that we live in a time of unprecedented prosperity; Stephen Pinker has argued strongly that violence in human civilization is on a continuous downward trend, and that the time we live in is one of unprecedented peace (</span><i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">The Better Angels of our Nature</span></i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">, 2011.). This is a bitter pill to swallow for those of us anticipating the Apocalypse, but the good news for us is that such optimism doesn\'t mean that climate change isn\'t real, or that the Technological Singularity isn\'t coming, or that we are not accelerating towards political collapse.</span></span></p><p><span style=\"font-size: 20px;\"><b>10010</b></span></p><p><span style=\"font-size: 20px;\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">What it </span><i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">does</span></i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> mean is that our assumptions about the world have been overtaken by the social, economic and technological changes happening around us, leaving us stuck with a picture of the present that doesn\'t reflect reality accurately. For example: after decolonisation, the West developed an unshakeable belief that Africa\'s economic narrative was one of chronic failure, but recent research suggests that this failure was a statistical artefact that only holds true if you ignore the 1950s, 1960s, 1970s and then the 1990s and 2000s (Morten, 2015. </span><i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Africa: Why Economists Get It Wrong</span></i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">). Statistics are always suspect, of course, and measurement is a form of magic, yet African countries turn out educated young people into economies that provide them with no jobs, just the same as Europe does, and it\'s economic progress that links those countries to international trade networks which can export commodities  or people. The migrants arrive on the beaches of Europe carrying mobile phones, and we\'re surprised to hear our demographic and technological future asking for our wi-fi password.</span></span></p><p><span style=\"font-size: 20px;\"><b>10100</b></span></p><p><span style=\"font-weight: 400; font-size: 20px;\">The movements described here are relatively insignificant in terms of numbers, but they provide us with insight, with instruction. They are presented as conversion experiences, they foresee an Apocalypse, and they call on their proponents to steer civilisation towards the Rapture. The task of the enlightened is to care for the rest of us on that journey; going back to Berardi, they have the role of attending to those [hopeless and depressed and panicking] people and taking care of their insanity, showing them the way of a happy adaptation at hand. Perhaps Marinetti was right to target his automobile towards aesthetic rather than political ends, even though the political is always embedded in the aesthetic. There is no escaping the unbearable present, because it has already collapsed into the future, but at least these stories can distract us from the landscape as it speeds past the windows.</span></p><p><span style=\"font-size: 20px;\"><b>10101</b></span></p><p><span style=\"font-size: 20px;\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">In his last book before an early death, the political scientist Peter Mair wrote of how the model of democratic politics was being hollowed out as the mass political parties died off (</span><i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Ruling the Void: the Hollowing of Western Democracy</span></i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">, 2014.). Those parties were the vehicles for our stories, telling us that things were once better than they are now and/or that things would be better in the future than they are now. When Srnicek and Williams argue that the left can neither remain in the present nor return to the past, (</span><i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Inventing the Future</span></i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">, 2015.) they are only partially correct, because the movements described here suggest that we can\'t get back to the future, either. As the past and the future have collapsed into the present, both left and right have collapsed into a new politics of the present; and the shape of this new politics is unclear, heavily contested, in permanent beta. Marinetti\'s roaring automobile is now a self-driving car, waiting for somebody  anybody  to seize the steering wheel.</span></span></p><p><span style=\"font-size: 20px;\"><b>GOTO 0</b></span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"font-size: 16px;\"><b>References</b></span></p><ol><li><span style=\"font-size: 16px;\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> Barbrook, Richard and Cameron, Andy (2007) </span><i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">The Californian Ideology</span></i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">. Dostupno na: <a href=\"http://www.comune.torino.it/gioart/big/bigguest/riflessioni/%20californian_engl.pdf\">http://www.comune.torino.it/gioart/big/bigguest/riflessioni/ californian_engl.pdf</a></span></span></li><li><span style=\"font-size: 16px;\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> Barlow, John Perry (1996) </span><i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">A Declaration of Cyberspace Independence</span></i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">. Dostupno na: <a href=\"https://www.eff.org/cyberspace-independence\">https://projects.eff.org/~barlow/Declaration-Final.html</a></span></span></li><li><span style=\"font-size: 16px;\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> Berardi, Franco (2009) </span><i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">The Post-Futurist Manifesto</span></i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">. Dostupno na: <a href=\"http://www.generation-online.org/p/fp_bifo5.htm\">http://www.generation-online.org/p/fp_bifo5.htm</a></span></span></li><li><span style=\"font-size: 16px;\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> Berardi, Franco (2009) </span>