	(269,1,'2016-11-07 20:29:46','2016-11-07 20:29:46','[:sr]<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Nakon<span>[fusnota]Tekst je izvorno predstavljen na globalnom umetnikom forumu Art Dubai \" Menadment razoarenja: umetnici i publika\", odranom u Ujedinjenim Arapskim Emiratima marta 2011. godine, a potom objavljen u Iranskom asopisu Art Tomorrow, br. 4, prolee 2011, strana 172-181. Ovde preveden i objavljen uz dozvolu autora.</span><span>[/fusnota]</span> nocnog leta srednje duzine, odlazeci ili dolazeci na sledeci sastanak/ konsultaciju/konferenciju/simpozijum/ gig/vikend u gradu, upadas u taksi. Osecas privremeno olaksanje sto barem mozes sa vozacem da procaskas na svom maternjem ili pak drugom jeziku koji najbolje poznajes. Meutim, iznenada si zbunjen jer postaje jasno da vozac svakako ne razume sta si rekao, i da ni jedan od jezika koji obicno govoris njemu nije razumljiv. Gde si ti bese? Ponovo mu dajes adresu, ovog puta bez upotrebe pretpostavljenog zajednickog govornog aparata, i kako vozac odmice od aerodroma uveren si da iako nisi odrastao ovde, ovo mesto do sada vec dovoljno dobro poznajes. Sve je onako kako se secas, sa jos po nekim novim oblakoderom, nastavkom gradnje u okolini aerodroma i sa jos nekoliko internacionalnih lanaca prodavnica koje oblazu spoljasnja predgraa grada. </span></p><p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Zbog radova na novoj liniji lakog metroa koji povezuje grad sa aerodromom, radova koji se, kako izgleda, nikada nece zavrsiti, dolazi do zastoja u saobracaju, tako da igrom srecnih okolnosti vozac nastavlja zaobilaznim putem i dovodi te u deo grada za koji si cuo ali nikada do sada nisi imao prilike da posetis. Nekada zapusten, poznat po propalim i zatvorenim prodavnicama i malim fabrikama, sada je nasminkan nekolicinom kafica, restorana, galerija, butika i klubova, diskretno najavljujuci deo onoga u sta se ovaj kraj pretvara. Skromni izlozi skrivaju ponudu, promovisuci tako vecu prisnost sa robom unutar same prodavnice. Dovoljno dobro si upoznat sa svim ovim strategijama. Jos uvek u raskoraku sa, dzet legom iseckanim, nervnim sistemom, odlucujes da napravis samo mentalnu belesku nekoliko mesta na koje ces se vratiti nakon sto zavrsis sa pripremama i sastancima koji ti slede. Sa sajta dobro upucenog city guide-a, koji si bukmarkovao na tvom inace beskorisnom iPad-u saznaces vec gde vredi otici. U meuvremenu nastavljas da sa upola paznje gledas kroz prozor taksija, primecujuci da je sva odeca u izlozima koja se prodaje kao unikatna, ista kao iz mesta iz koga si upravo dosao i nekog drugog gde ces otici za nekih deset dana. Mikro-lokalna verzija globalnog brenda sik jakne koju upravo nosis.</span></p><p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Zaustavljajuci se na semaforu samo trenutak pre izlaska iz ovog kraja nalazis sebe zagledanog kroz prozor taksija u umetnicko delo postavljeno na oko 3 metra unutar, neonskim svetlom, osvetljene galerije. Tvoja prva pomisao je da te rad na neki udaljen nacin podseca na komad koji ti je privukao paznju u jednom umetnickom magazinu proslog meseca. Ne secas se ni umetnika ni izlozbe, jedino da je glavni kurator LACMA-e bio na otvaranju. Pocinjes da skreces pogled sa galerijskog prostora, kao i sa svih drugih prozora i izloga, jedva cekajuci samo da does u svoj apartman, da se istusiras, organizujes, mozda na kratko odspavas ili treniras pre prvog sastanka koji ti sledi za cetiri sata.</span></p><p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Meutim, takoe zatices sebe kako i dalje gledas u ovaj rad, primecujuci, samo nekoliko trenutaka pre nego sto ce se taksi udaljiti, ime umetnika napisano Helvetika stensil slovima</span></p><p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">na prozoru, i ispod i sa desne strane, ime galerije za koju bez previse iznenaenja saznajes da se preselila sa prethodne, pomalo izolovane lokacije. Prisecas se toga bez obzira na nelagodnost koju osecas jer si je, jos pre osam meseci, ipak vec trazio i zapravo skoro doneo neki art tamo. Iako to nije bas ispalo kako treba, uspostavio si dobar odnos sa galeristkinjom - ti si verovao njoj i ona je verovala tebi u dovoljnoj meri da budes smatran kolekcionarom jednog od njenih bolje poznatih umetnika. Dopala ti se njena ozbiljnost i zahvalnost zbog tvog interesovanja za umetnost i dizajn u tako mnogo gradova.</span></p><p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Kasnije tog dana, kada si dosao sebi od posledica puta, nalazis sebe kako si sa vremena na vreme zaokupljen galerijama, kvartovima grada, umetnoscu. Cekirajuci lokalni art vodic na svom iPad-u saznajes da ona ista galerija koju si primetio iz taksija veceras ima otvaranje i, nakon par SMS-ova, azuriranja svog Facebook i Twiter profila, dogovaras da se naes tamo</span></p><p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">sa prijateljicom. Meutim ne vidis to samo kao neko mesto za sastajanje. Ostao si zaintrigiran onim kratkim iskustvom umetnickog rada koje si imao: njegova postavka u prostoru ukazala je na inteligentnost i samosvest; utisak koji si dobio, cinio ti se samo kao stvar trenutka, dok si takoe prepoznao da je igra formi u radu duboko usaena u jedan kulturni zargon koji ti se dopada i kao da je izgledalo da cela stvar trazi vise od tebe kako bi se konacno zaokruzila. Za razliku od robe iz obliznjih prodavnica koja se, kao sto to veoma dobro razumes, obraca tebi tako da govori nesto o tvojoj potrosnji, ova umetnost izgleda kao da trazi nesto od tebe. Rad te intrigira. Zelis ponovo da ga vidis. Razmisljas da ga kupis.</span></p><p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Meutim nisi bas siguran: iako znas da ova vrsta umetnosti dobija na popularnosti, ipak si video ovaj komad samo na trenutak, a umetnica ti je nepoznata. Cekiras ArtFacts i saznajes da je rangirana ne bas toliko nisko i to ti daje odreeno samopouzdanje: izlagala je pomalo po inostranstvu, imala par izlozbi u institucijama, meutim jos uvek nije toliko priznata da bi joj cene bile nepristupacne. Umetnica je u usponu i shvatajuci to, odjednom se osecas pokrenut entuzijazmom, kojem se, samo nekoliko casova pre toga, nisi nadao. Podstaknut si da pozoves galeriju i nakon par razmenjenih ljubaznih reci sa galeristkinjom ugovoras sastanak malo pre otvaranja.</span></p><p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">U taksiju na putu prema galeriji, zelis jos malo da se uveris i saljes informacije o umetnici svom savetniku za umetnost, nadajuci se da je u vremenskoj zoni odakle ce moci da ti odgovori na vreme pre nego sto stignes u galeriju. Imas srece: tvoj savetnik se nalazi na sajmu umetnost tri sata iza tebe i odmah odgovara - Sent from my Blackberry  govoreci da iako postoje price o ovoj umetnici, da se one trenutno svode samo na jedan ili dva grada; da je izlozba na koju upravo ides njena prva u regionu u kojem se nalazis; da je veoma bitno to sto galeristkinja koja ponovo otvara galeriju na novoj lokaciji, bas nju u ovom novom prostoru prikazuje, i jos par traceva koji te istovremeno uzbuuju i dosadni su ti.</span></p><p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Ne stizes da razmislis o svemu ovome a vec si stigao, i kratko vreme si sam sa izlozbom. Prosavsi kroz prostor vracas se na rad koji si ugledao kroz staklo taksija, sto ti sada izgleda danima daleko. Onakav je kakav ti je ostao u secanju ali, posto si razmisljao o njemu u satima pre dolaska, pocinjes jos vise da ga cenis, laknulo ti je, nalazis da nastavlja da nagrauje tvoju zainteresovanost za njega. Nalazeci najbolje uglove iz kojih ces ga posmatrati, kontemplirajuci ga, ispitujuci odnos izmeu njegove ideje i forme, on hrani i zadovoljava tvoju radoznalost na nacin na koji smatras da umetnost to radi najbolje. Volis umetnost upravo zbog toga sto ti daje vreme da pronaes sopstveni put kroz nju.</span></p><p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Iako nisi ni primetio kada je dosla, galeristkinja je vec pored tebe. Fantastican rad, izgovara tiho, zagledana u njega zajedno sa tobom. Nakon pozdrava i malo caskanja, ponovo pauza dok zajedno stojite zagledani u delo. Kazes koliko cenis ton i emociju samog dela, njegov senzibilitet. Galeristkinja ti odgovara da je to upravo ono sto je tako vazno u praksi ove umetnice, zajedno sa komuniciranjem i priblizavanjem tradicija umetnosti savremenoj publici, koje su, kako si to vec prepoznao, inspiracija za umetnicu. Galeristkinja ti dalje govori da nam umetnica ukazuje na epohu u kojoj je izgledalo da umetnost ima centralno mesto u drustvenim i estetskim promenama, odlucujuci trenutak modernosti. Slazes se: ovo umetnicko delo priblizava te toj snazi, jednoj liniji transformacije koja ti se meutim sada ne namece, dopustajuci ti da stvoris sopstveni smisao samog dela. Pominjes galeristkinji ovaj zanimljivi odnos prema istoriji. Slaze se, i zadivljena tvojim entuzijazmom i postovanjem za umetnost, insistira da prisustvujes veceri nakon otvaranja. Ljubazno prihvatas i koristis priliku da pokrenes razgovor o ceni dela. Galeristkinja nagovestava da bi nesto bilo moguce srediti, ali imajuci na umu sve faktore koje treba uzeti u obzir, kao i da ovo nije ni mesto ni vreme da se donese bilo kakva odluka, ali ipak primetivsi tvoje ocekivanje popusta, ona odlucuje da ti ga rezervise.</span></p><p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Kasnije tokom otvaranja galeristkinja te upoznaje sa umetnicom. Uprkos tvojoj zelji da pricas sa njom, opet si obeshrabren jer zapravo ne razumes nista sto ti govori. Nemoguce da je u pitanju tvoj engleski, buduci da si ga stekao obrazovanjem u najboljim americkim skolama i njihovim ograncima u drugim zemljama, koliko i tvojim kosmopolitskim zivotom posle toga. Nije u pitanju to sta ona govori, jer iako ti jezik zvuci blisko ne mozes da uhvatis znacenje nijedne reci zbog akcenta. Tvoja zbunjenost raste jer umetnica ima anglosaksonsko ime, i mala grupa ljudi u kojoj se ti i ona sada nalazite je internacionalna tako da bi trebalo da se govori engleski. Nakon nekog vremena od nekoga iz grupe saznajes da je ona skotlananka i postaje ti jasno zbog cega je nisi razumeo. Sad cak pocinjes da hvatas poneku frazu. Umetnica izrazava duboko postovanje za relativno nepoznatog umetnika visokog modernizma, i drago ti je sto si ranije uvideo nesto od toga u samom delu. Zakljucujes na osnovu reakcija drugih da umetnica prihvata razlicite ideje o znacenju njenog rada jer zeli da on bude otvoren interpretaciji publike, pozdravljajuci razovrsnost gledista. Zapravo je rasprava o radu, kaze ona, sa iznenadnom snagom i jasnocom, sama sustina njenog rada. Naravno citava ova prica nije odlazila previse duboko, ipak je ovo samo otvaranje - meutim dovoljno je da te ponovo uveri da umetnost zaista poseduje jednu slozenost ideja i emocija</span></p><p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">do kojih ti je stalo, da iako ne poznajes umetnicu licno ti uprkos tome mozes da osetis neku vezu sa njom kroz njenu umetnost. Ona ocekuje od svoje publike da bude inteligentna kao ti, ukljucujuci te kao individuu. Prepoznajes da ce se njena interesovanja razvijati u pravcu koji bi mogao da sledis. Odlucujes da joj ne spomenes svoju zainteresovanost za komad, kako na otvaranju iznenada ne bi osetila nelagodnost sa tobom. U svakom slucaju, mozete o tome da pricate jos kada ona to bude pokrenula.</span></p><p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Dok te voze na veceru prireenu povodom otvaranja izlozbe, tvoja prijateljica te zamara njenim idejama o investiranju u kraj u kome se smestila galerija, koriscenju prilike koju grad pruza promenom zoniranja i smanjenjem taksi kako bi se podstakao rast malih kreativnih preduzeca, privukle strane investicije i tako dalje. Cuo si sve to vec ranije i zvuci ti previse kao tvoj dnevni posao (ako ti je vise uopste i jasno sta znaci dnevni, pored svih tih putovanja koja obavljas). Suvise si uzbuen zbog onoga sto veceras sledi i ubrzo skreces razgovor na mogucu kupovinu dela. Razmatras sa prijateljicom koji bi od tvojih apartmana bio najbolje mesto za rad, ali si gotovo siguran da to treba da bude mesto na kojem ces provesti najvise vremena u godini koja dolazi. Cesto to radis sa novim delima kako bi ti ona postala bliska, nagraujuci tvoju zaiteresovanost koja ne prestaje. Prepoznajes meutim i da je otvaranjem ove izlozbe, galeristkinja njen prostor uzdigla na nivo internacionalne umetnicke scene, nimalo se ne ogranicavajuci lokalim interesima, da se o tom delu grada vec pisalo u nekoliko vodica koje si preleteo na svom iPad-u, i da je na otvaranju bilo krcato ne samo uobicajnom gomilom entuzijasta i namcorastim lokalnim umetnicima, vec i nekim ljudima koji su dosli u napucanim kolima, takoe podsecas sebe da bi ipak trebalo pitati prijateljicu o lokalnim investicionim prilikama, jer se ovde nesto ocigledno dogaa.</span></p><p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Tokom vecere osecas olaksanje sto ne sedis blizu umetnice jer i dalje ne mozes da skapiras njen akcenat. Meutim dovoljno si blizu i nje i galeristkinje da se ne mogu osecati uvreeno. Ukljucujes se u zanimljiv razgovor sa nekoliko lokalnih kolekcionara, umetnika i kriticara. Zanima ih tvoje misljenje o radovima umetnice, o gradovima i umetnickim scenama u koje si dobro upucen, kao i tvoji stavovi o razvoju regiona u tom kontekstu. Jedana od kriticarki te poziva da das intervju za njihov magazin, na temu dostupnosti i vaznosti kolekcionarstva za razvoj kulturne ekonomije i identiteta regiona u vremenu globalizacije. Polaskan si, osecas da ona razume da svi mi sada zivimo u jednom povezanom svetu, da oseca kako tvoje interesovanje za umetnost komunicira ovu sveopstu povezanost, sto ti omogucava da razmisljas o odnosu izmeu mesta iz koga ti dolazis i mesta iz koga dolazi umetnik. Razbiras sve to po glavi dok razmenjujes vizit karte sa kriticarkom, radujuci se trenutku kada ces joj pokazati svoju kolekciju. Kasnije cim se ukazala prilika da nasamo popricas sa galeristkinjom, ugovaras kupovinu. Bilo je to veoma dobro vece i napustas ga, sad vec dovoljno ohrabren da pokusas da ues cak i u direktan razgovor sa umetnicom.</span></p><p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Dva meseca kasnije delo je postavljeno u tvom stanu, i za ono nekoliko puta koliko si bio tamo, primecujes kako postajes jos vise entuzijastican sposobnostima umetnice da prizove najvazniju vrednost umetnosti na tako licnom i neposrednom nivou. Razgovaras sa svojim savetnikom za umetnost o tvojoj zadivljenosti ovom umetnicom i on ti predlaze da zajedno posetite njenu maticnu galeriju kako biste videli sta oni jos imaju dostupno. Srecom posao te sledeceg meseca odvodi bas u taj grad i savetnik ti zakazuje sastanak. Dok si tamo saznajes da trenutno nista od njenih radova nije dostupno, ali da galerija planira da predstavi umetnicu na njihovom sledecem sajmu umetnosti. Izrazavas veliko interesovanje i uveravas galeriju da ce ti raspored omoguciti da budes na sajmu. Na predotvaranju sajma, zahvaljujuci tvojim vezama sa galeristkinjom sa kojom si prvobitno imao posla, obezbeujes sledeci komad po snizenoj ceni.</span></p><p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Tri meseca kasnije: obezbedio si jos jedan rad sa prve izlozbe umetnice u Njujorku. Ne mozes da budes tamo ali tvoj savetnik za umetnost sreuje detalje za tebe. Zadovoljan si sto saznajes da si jedan od vodecih kolekcionara radova ove umetnice: verujes da je vredi podrzati, da njen rad zasluzuje paznju i vidljivost koju dobija u magazinima i casopisima, da sa njenom umetnickom inteligentnoscu i osetilnoscu nisi saglasan samo ti, vec i tvoje kolege i prijatelji koji su vecinom impresionirani njenom umetnoscu, koja se sada vec nalazi u vise prostora u kojima zivis.</span></p><p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Godinu dana kasnije sa istinskim zadovoljstvom primas poziv od maticne galerije umetnice da za potrebe izlozbe u muzeju jednog od glavnih metropolitskih centara pozajmis jedno od njenih dela. Posebno si uzbuen zato sto je u pitanju jedan od gradova u kojem provodis najvise vremena i vec neko vreme cenis izlozbe tradicionalnih radova iz razlicitih regiona postavljenih zajedno sa delima savremene umetnosti koje taj isti muzej organizuje. Kad god si mogao da posetis te izlozbe, sa obzirom na tvoj gust raspored, bio si impresioniran pronalazenjem estetskih i kulturnih vrednosti koje te razlicite tradicije imaju u danasnjem svetu. Bez ustezanja prihvatas pozajmicu koju organizujes preko svog savetnika za umetnost. On obezbeuje mesto za tebe i njega na ekskluzivnom rucku povodom otvaranja izlozbe.</span></p><p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Pored odreene sumnje u to da li je umetnicin rad na najbolji nacin postavljen na izlozbi, takoe shvatas da je prisustvo njenog rada na ovoj izlozbi dobro za njen profil. Umetnica je</span></p><p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">u isto vreme i pomalo nervozna i pomalo uzbuena svojim prisustvom na izlozbi. Imajuci u vidu to da si uspeo donekle da shvatis njen izgovor do sada, upustas se u neobavezan razgovor i razmenjujes nekoliko sala sa njom kako bi je oraspolozio tokom formalnosti otvaranja. Tokom vecere, ponovo zatices sebe kako sa entuzijazmom pricas o tome koliko cenis umetnicu, izlozbu i muzej, o potrebi promocije istorije i tradicije umetnosti, i kako su muzeji pogodna mesta za to jer na kraju krajeva istorija i jeste njihov posao. Ostavljas jak utisak na predstavnicu komisije muzeja za koju sa zadovoljstvom saznajes da vec zna nesto o tebi. I pored toga ipak si pomalo iznenaen (i zadovoljan) kada za otprilike mesec dana posle ove vecere od nje dobijas mejl u kome te poziva da prisustvujes rucku sa prijateljima muzeja i njegovim direktorom. Na rucku, direktor muzeja napominje kako je od nedavno upraznjeno jedno mesto u odboru savetnika i pita te da razmotris ponudu. Ti si naravno odusevljen ponudom ali se pravis pomalo nezainteresovan i odgovaras jedino da ces razmisliti o tome. Direktor muzeja napominje da svaki takav izbor zavisi od formalnog poziva, procedure provere (iz razloga odgovornosti prema javnosti) a mozda cak i panel diskusije. Ovaj odgovor izaziva odreenu alarmantnost kod tebe. Da li je trebalo da budes manje neodlucan u svom odgovoru? Uveravas sebe da su ovo standardne procedure koje bi u svakom slucaju morale biti preduzete. I naravno, otprilike nedelju dana kasnije dobijas pozivno pismo da postanes savetnik muzeja koji od tebe trazi da doprineses njegovom buducem razvoju a na osnovu tvog velikog interesovanja za promociju savremene umetnosti. Prihvatas ovaj poziv prosavsi kroz ritualne procese imenovanja sa sigurnoscu i lakocom. Upitan zbog cega zelis da preuzmes dodatni napor koji dolazi sa tako malim obestecenjem, nalazis sebe kako razmisljas o umetnosti koja te je isprva dovela u vezu sa muzejem i to ti daje samopouzdanje da na istinski i sustinski nacin govoris o svojoj strasti i verovanju u ono sto umetnost moze da ucini za pojedinca kao sto si ti.</span></p><p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Uskoro nalazis sebe kako koristis znanje iz oblasti investicija i razvoja kako bi savetovao muzej u njegovoj strategiji prosirenja. To te uzbuuje obzirom da ti se cini da to znanje izgleda posebno korisno gledano prema parametrima onoga sto ti mislis da je veoma vazno u umetnosti danas: isticanje licnog susreta sa njom, njenu otvorenost prema diskusiji, njen snazan edukativni aspekt kroz iznosenje vaznih tema u javnost, bez da to cini nametljivo, njenu inkluzivnost. Ono sto nastavlja da te inspirise, uprkos ponekad dosadnom ali vaznom poslu koji si pozvan da radis, jeste to da je poslovanje muzeja sada u samom centru strategije razvoja regiona u kome muzej igra centralnu ulogu. Ti igras svoju skromnu ali opet vaznu ulogu u svemu tome. Promovisuci javnu edukaciju koja je na odgovarajuci nacin osetljiva prema kompleksnosti sveta, time sto podrzavas ono sto nalazis da je najvrednije od umetnosti, osecas da si pronasao nesto sto te najbolje predstavlja u javnosti, nesto vredno truda, ne samo za tebe, vec i za sve nas. </span></p>[:en]<p>Slumping<span>[fusnota]This article is based on a talk presented at \'Disappointment Management: Artists &amp; Audiences\', Global Art Forum_5, Art Dubai, UAE, March 14-18, 2011</span><span>[/fusnota]</span> into the taxi after your overnight medium-haul flight to or from the next board meeting/consultancy/conference/symposium/gig/weekend-city-break, you feel temporarily relieved to be able to at least speak to the driver in your native or second language. But then youre suddenly confused because its clear that the driver doesnt easily understand what youve said anyway and none of the languages you regularly use are his. So where are you again? You give him the address once more, this time without the conversational apparatus of familiarity, and as he pulls away from the airport youre reassured that even if you didnt grow up here you know this place fairly well by now. Everything is where you remember it, given one or two new towers, an extension of the development around the airport and a couple more international chain stores lining the outer suburbs of the city.</p><p>But the traffics grinding to a halt because the work on the new light-rail connection to the airport seems to be carrying on forever, so the driver takes a detour fortuitously bringing you into an area of the city you had heard of but not yet had a chance to visit. Formerly a bit battered, known for its closing and failing retail and light industrial businesses, its now peppered with a few cafes, restaurants, galleries, boutiques and clubs only discreetly announcing themselves to be, just as precisely, part of what is arriving, not leaving the area. The displays in what windows there are understate the cause of their merchandise, promoting the greater intimacy of your encounter with them within the boutiques. Youre familiar enough with all these strategies.</p><p>Still caught in the deferrals of your jet-lag shredded nervous-system, you decide to only make a mental note of one or two places youll return to later once youre through the preparation and meetings directly ahead of you. Youll find out where is worth going from the city insider guide website bookmarked on your otherwise disappointing iPad. Meantime, you continue to look half-curiously out of the taxi window, noting that though the clothes on display are all evidently made in the boutiques selling them as unique items, theyd have also worked really well where you just came from and where youll be going in about ten days. A micro-local version of the globally chic fashion-house diffusion-range jacket youre wearing right now.</p><p>Stopping at a light just before you leave the area you find yourself gazing through the taxi window at an artwork placed about 3 meters into a neon-lit gallery space. Your first reaction is that it reminds you in a distant way of a piece that caught your attention in the art magazine newsletter last month. You dont remember the artist or venue, only that the Chief Curator of LACMA was at the opening. You start to turn away from the gallery space as you have from all the other windows and fronts, looking forward now just to getting back to your place, to shower, organize yourself, maybe have a quick recuperative sleep or workout before your first meeting in four hours time. But you also find yourself continuing to look at this art, noting just before the cab pulls away the name of the artist, presented in Helvetica stencil-lettering on the window, and below it and to the right, that of the gallery which you are not too surprised to learn has moved from its previous slightly too isolated location. You recall that despite that inconvenience you nonetheless sought it out eight months ago and in fact nearly brought some art there. Even though that didnt quite work out, you and the gallerist had a good rapport  you trusted her and she trusted you enough to be considered as a collector of one of her better known artists. You liked the seriousness and her appreciation of your interest in art and design in so many cities.</p><p>Later that day, having extricated yourself enough from the dislocations of travel, you find yourself occasionally pre-occupied with the gallery, the area, the art. Checking the local art guide on your iPad you find out that the gallery has its opening that evening and, after a few SMSs, updates of your Facebook page and tweets, you arrange to meet a friend there. But you are not especially thinking about it as just a meeting place. Youve remained intrigued by the glimpse of the work you had: its presentation in the space showed an intelligence and self-awareness; what images you could make out in it seemed somehow of the moment while you also recognized its play of forms to be rooted in the cultural vernaculars you like; and the way the whole thing seemed to want <u>more of you</u> for it to come together. Unlike the goods in the boutiques nearby which, as you understand very well, presents itself to you so as to say something about you in its consumption, this art seems to ask something of you. The work intrigues you. You want to see more of it. You think of buying it.</p><p>But you are not sure: while you know that this kind of art is beginning to get some exposure, you only saw this piece for less than a minute, and the artist is unfamiliar to you. You check ArtFacts and see that she is ranked in the low thousands and this gives you a certain confidence: she has shown a bit internationally, had a couple of exhibitions in public spaces, but is not established enough for her prices to be out of reach. The artist is on the way up and recognizing this suddenly propels you into an enthusiasm you didnt think was available to you even a few hours before, spurring you to call the gallery and, after exchanging some pleasantries with the gallerist, arranging to meet her at the space just before the opening.</p><p>In the cab going to the gallery you seek some reassurance, emailing your art advisor about the artist, hoping that he is in a timezone where he will be able to answer you before you get there. Youre in luck: hes at an artfair three hours behind you and answers immediately - Sent from my Blackberry - saying that though theres a buzz about the artist its still contained at the moment to one or two cities; that the show you are about to go to is the first in the region you are in; that its taken as a real sign of the gallerist having arrived that she is showing the artist in the new space; and some other gossip which simultaneously titillates and bores you.</p><p>Before you have time to process all of this, you arrive and you are alone with the show for a few minutes in the empty space. Taking a walk through it you return to the piece you saw through the taxi window from what now feels like days away. It is as you remember it but, having grown in your mind in the hours since arriving, you appreciate it more and, relieved, you find that it continues to reward your interest in it. Finding the right places to see it from, exploring it in your mind, examining the interplay between its ideas and its forms, it feeds and satisfies your curiosity in the way you find art does best. You like art precisely because it gives you this time to find your way through it.</p><p>The gallerist is by your side without you noticing how she got there. An amazing work, she says quietly, gazing at it with you. After some greetings and small talk, a pause as you both stare at the work again. You say how much you appreciate the tone and feel of the piece, its sensitivity. The gallerist tells you that this is exactly what is so important for the artist in her practice, together with humanizing for a contemporary audience the historical traditions of art that, as you have already recognized, were an inspiration for her. The gallerist says that the artist reminds us all of an epoch when art seemed central to social and aesthetic changes, a decisive moment of modernity. You agree: the artwork brings you close to that impetus, a vector of transformation yet one that now doesnt force your hand, allowing you to make your own sense of the work. You mention this intriguing play with history to the gallerist. She agrees and, impressed with your enthusiasm and appreciation of the art, insists that you attend the aftershow dinner. You humbly acquiesce and take advantage of the opportunity to broach the subject of the price of the work. The gallerist suggests something may be possible but, given all the factors that need to be taken into account, and recognizing that this is not a place or time to resolve anything, you settle with her that she reserve it for you while noting your expectation of a discount.</p><p>Later at the opening, the gallerist introduces you to the artist. Despite your enthusiasm to talk to her, you are unnerved once more because you dont really understand anything she is saying. It cant be your English, since that has been honed by your graduate schooling in the best American schools and their offshore campuses, as much as the internationalism of your life since. And it isnt anything she may saying because you just cant make out any of the words through the accent. Your confusion is compounded since the artist has an Anglo name and the small group you and she are in are from the usual wide range of places and so are speaking English. Then you catch from someone in the group that she is Scottish and your incomprehension now makes sense to you. You can now even begin to pick out the occasional phrase. The artist expresses a deep appreciation of a relatively unknown high modernist and you are pleased that you understood something of this in the work. You gather from responses to what she is saying that she welcomes different ideas of what her work may be about because she wants it to be open to whatever the audience makes of it, welcoming the divergence of views on it. It is in fact the discussion of her work, she says with sudden force and clarity, that is the very point of the work.</p><p>Of course, none of this is taken up in too much depth  it is after all only the opening night but its enough to reassure you that the art really has the complexity of ideas and sensitivity that matters to you, that even though you have little in common with her personally you can nonetheless share something through her art. She recognizes her audience to be intelligent as you are, engaging you as an individual. You intuit that her interests will develop in a way that you can stay with. You choose not to mention your interest in the piece to her in case she would suddenly feel uncomfortable with you at the opening. In any case, you can always speak more about it when she installs it.</p><p>Being driven to the after-show dinner, your friend tires you with her interest in investing in the area the gallery has set up in, taking advantage of the rezoning and tax breaks offered by the city to encourage small-scale creative enterprises, draw international investment and so on. Youve heard all this before and it sounds too much like your day job (if you could get a grip on what day meant anymore through all the traveling you do). You are too excited about the evening and quickly turn the conversation to your potential purchase of the piece. You discuss with your friend which of your apartments the art would be best be best placed but you feel pretty clear that it should be where you will be spending the most time in the coming year. You often do this with new work so you can get to know it intimately, rewarding your sustained interest in it. Recognising however that by putting on this show the gallerist has pitched her space at the level of the international artscene rather than parochial interests, that the area was already being written about in several of the style guides you scanned on your iPad, and that the opening was busy enough not only with the usual ragbag of enthusiastic or sour local artists but also some people arriving in very statement cars, you also make a mental note to ask your friend soon about the local investment opportunities since something is clearly happening here.</p><p>Over dinner you are a bit relieved not to be sat to close to the artist since you still cant get through her accent. But close enough to both her and the gallerist to not feel offended, you engage in interesting conversations with a couple of local collectors, artists and artcritics. They are interested in what you have to say about the artists work, your views on the other cities and artscenes you know well, and your thoughts on the development of the region in that context. One of the critics proposes interviewing you for their magazine, for a feature on the accessibility and importance of art collecting to developing the regions cultural economy and identity in an age of globalization. You are flattered by this, feeling that she understands something of how we now all live in an interconnected world, how your interest in art expresses this inter-connectedness for you, allowing you to find something for yourself in relation to where you are and where the artists come from, what your respective interests are. You preview all this in your head as exchange cards with the critic, looking forward to showing her around your collection. Later, when you get a chance to talk more closely with the gallerist, you finalise the deal. It has been a very good evening and you leave it encouraged enough to even attempt a direct conversation with the artist as you leave</p><p>Two months later the piece is installed for you and on the few times you are in that apartment you find yourself becoming ever more enthusiastic about the artists ability to recall arts most important values at such a personal and immediate level. You discuss your enthusiasm for the artist with your art advisor and he recommends you visit the artists home gallery with him to see what else they have available. Luckily, your business takes you to that city in the next month and he sets up the appointment for you. While there, you learn that nothing is available at this moment in time but the gallery will feature the artist in their next art-fair presentation. You express a strong interest and ensure that your schedule allows you to be there. Thanks to your relationship to the gallerist you initially dealt with, you secure a second piece at a discounted price at the fairs pre-opening viewing session.</p><p>Three months after that: you secure another piece form the artists first show in New York. You cant be there but your art advisor takes care of the details. You are pleased to learn that you are now one of the leading collectors of this artists work: you believe that she is worth standing behind, that her work deserves the exposure and attention it is getting in the magazines and journals, that her artistic intelligence and sensitivity accords not just with your own but also that of your colleagues and your friends who have mostly been impressed with her art, which you now have set up in more than one of your living spaces.</p><p>So its with genuine pleasure that you receive a request form the artists main gallery a year later to lend one of the works to a museum show in a major metropolitan center. You are especially excited because it is in one the cities where you spend the most time and you have appreciated for some time the museums exhibitions of traditional work from different regions curated with contemporary art. When you can get to these shows given your busy schedule you have seen have impressed with their commitment to finding an aesthetic and cultural merit in todays world for these various traditions. You have no problem agreeing to the loan which you arrange through your art advisor. He secures a place for you and himself at the exclusive pre-public launch for the museum show.</p><p>Though you have some reservations as to whether the artists work has been best served by how it has been installed in the exhibition, you also recognize that its appearance in the show is very good for the artists profile. The artist herself is at once nervous and very excited to be in the show. Having by now come to understand her speech somewhat, you make small talk and share a few jokes with her to re-assure her during the formalities of the opening. At the dinner, you again find yourself speaking with enthusiasm about your appreciation for the artist, the exhibition and the museum, the need to promote awareness of histories and traditions of art and beyond in a globalized world, and how museums are very well suited for this since history is after all their business. You impress the Chair of the Museums Commissions Panel, whom you are pleased to learn already knows something about you. For all that, you are still a little surprised (and gratified) to receive an email from her a month or so later asking you to attend a lunch with friends of the Museum and its Director. At the lunch, the Director mentions that a space has recently emerged on the Board of Advisors and asks you to consider it. You are of course delighted to be asked but play it cool and tell him only that you will think about it. The Director mentions that any such appointment will all depend upon a formal invitation, a vetting procedure (for reasons of public accountability) and perhaps even a panel interview. This causes you a certain alarm. Should you have been less diffident in your response? You reassure yourself that these are standard processes that would have to be undertaken in any case. And indeed a week or so letter you receive a letter inviting you to be an Advisor to the Museum, asking for you to contribute to its future development on the basis of your keen interest in promoting contemporary art. You accept, going through the ritual processes of appointment with ease and comfort. Asked about why you would wish to take on the extra effort which comes with such little renumeration, you find yourself thinking of the art that brought you into contact with the museum in the first instance and this gives you the confidence to speak in real, substantial ways of your passion and belief in what art can do for individuals like yourself.</p><p>Very soon find yourself using your skills in investment and growth to advice the museum on its expansion strategy. This excites you since they seem especially respectful of the parameters that you think are important in art today: an emphasis on individual encounters with it, its opening to respectful debate, a strong educative aspect in its bringing important issues to peoples attention without being directing, inclusivity. What continues to inspire you through the sometimes dull but important work you are called onto do for the museum is that all of this is now at the core of the regions growth strategy in which the museum is playing a central role. You play your modest yet important part in this. Promoting a public education that is appropriately sensitive to the complexities of the world by supporting what you find best about art, you feel you have fond something that represents you best in public, something worthwhile not just for yourself but for all of us.</p>[:]','[:sr]Zbog ega umetnost? Primarnost publike[:en]Why Art? The Primacy of Audience[:]','','publish','closed','closed','','zbog-cega-umetnost-primarnost-publike','','','2016-11-07 21:00:30','2016-11-07 21:00:30','',0,'http://www.zentmagazine.com/?post_type=zent&#038;p=269',0,'zent','',0),
